[3] Malaysia - vector control
Date: Fri 28 Jan 2011
Source: Mmegionline [edited]
<http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?sid=1&aid=491&dir=2011/January/Friday28>


Malaysia has released 6000 genetically modified mosquitoes designed
to combat dengue fever in a landmark trial slammed Wednesday [26 Jan
2011] by environmentalists who say the experiment is unsafe. In the
1st experiment of its kind in Asia, about 6000 male_ Aedes aegypti_
mosquitoes were released at an uninhabited site in the central state
of Pahang, the government-run Institute of Medical Research (IMR)
said. The IMR, which was tasked with carrying out the trial, said the
experiment was conducted on 21 Dec [2010] to "study the dispersal and
longevity of these mosquitoes in the field. The experiment was
successfully concluded on 5 Jan 2011," the institute said in a
statement dated Tuesday [2 Feb 2011], adding that no further releases
are planned until the trial results are analysed.

The insects in the experiment have been engineered so that their
offspring quickly die, curbing the growth of the population in a
technique researchers hope could eventually eradicate the dengue
mosquito altogether.

Females of the _Aedes_ species are responsible for spreading dengue
[virus], [that causes] a deadly disease, which killed at least 134
people last year [2010] in Malaysia alone.

The trial has sparked widespread concern among environmental groups
and non-government organisations (NGOs), and had been postponed due
to their protests as well as unfavourable weather conditions.

"I am surprised that they did this without prior announcement given
the high level of concerns raised not just from the NGOs but also
scientists and the local residents," said researcher Lim Li Ching
from 3rd World Network. The network is part of 29 public health and
environmental groups which have repeatedly demanded the government
cancel the trial, saying it was risky and could lead to unintended
consequences.

"We don't agree with this trial that has been conducted in such an
un-transparent way. There are many questions, and not enough research
has been done on the full consequences of this experiment," she told
AFP. Critics have also said that too little is known about the
_Aedes_ mosquito and how the genetically modified insects would
interact with their cousins in the wild. Authorities have dismissed
the fears and said the trial would be harmless, as the GM mosquitoes
can live for only a few days.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[This is a preview of what reactions can be expected for release of
genetically modified vector arthropods. It underscores the need for
provision of ample public information and discussion in advance of
field experiments so that there is no accusation of secrecy and to
provide the experimenters with an opportunity to state the advantages
for public health and discussion of potential risks, if any, with
critics. Eradication of _Aedes aegypti_ through the release of
sufficient numbers of genetically modified males will be a challenge
in large cities having large and widespread populations of this
vector mosquito.

A map showing Malaysia's political division and the location of
Pahang state can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/malaysia_adm98.jpg>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Malaysia can be accessed
at <http://healthmap.org/promed/index.php?v=2.6,113.2,5>. - Mod.TY]

